<div class="container">

    <h1>CFOP Course</h1>

    <div class="case-card">

        <h2>What is CFOP?</h2>

        <p>
            CFOP is the most popular speedcubing method in the world.
            It is used by almost all professional speedcubers and world class solvers.
        </p>

        <p>
            CFOP stands for:
        </p>

        <p>
            <b>C</b>ross<br>
            <b>F</b>irst Two Layers (F2L)<br>
            <b>O</b>rient Last Layer (OLL)<br>
            <b>P</b>ermute Last Layer (PLL)
        </p>

    </div>

    <br>

    <div class="case-card">

        <h2>Step 1 — Cross</h2>

        <p>
            The first step is solving the cross on the bottom layer.
            Most speedcubers solve the white cross first.
        </p>

        <p>
            The goal is to solve four edge pieces while matching the side colors with the center pieces.
        </p>

    </div>

    <br>

    <div class="case-card">

        <h2>Step 2 — F2L</h2>

        <p>
            F2L stands for First Two Layers.
        </p>

        <p>
            In this step you pair a corner and edge together
            and insert them into their correct slot.
        </p>

        <p>
            There are 41 common F2L cases.
        </p>

        <p>
            Learning efficient F2L is one of the most important
            parts of becoming faster at speedcubing.
        </p>

    </div>

    <br>

    <div class="case-card">

        <h2>Step 3 — OLL</h2>

        <p>
            OLL stands for Orient Last Layer.
        </p>

        <p>
            This step solves all yellow stickers on the top layer.
        </p>

        <p>
            Full OLL contains 57 algorithms.
        </p>

        <p>
            Many beginners first learn 2-look OLL before learning all 57 cases.
        </p>

    </div>

    <br>

    <div class="case-card">

        <h2>Step 4 — PLL</h2>

        <p>
            PLL stands for Permute Last Layer.
        </p>

        <p>
            PLL moves the pieces into their correct positions
            after OLL is completed.
        </p>

        <p>
            Full PLL contains 21 algorithms.
        </p>

        <p>
            PLL is often considered one of the most fun
            parts of CFOP because of the fast algorithms.
        </p>

    </div>

    <br>

    <div class="case-card">

        <h2>How To Use This Website</h2>

        <p>
            Use the navigation bar at the top right to move between:
        </p>

        <p>
            • Notation<br>
            • F2L<br>
            • OLL<br>
            • PLL
        </p>

        <p>
            Every algorithm page contains progress tracking.
        </p>

        <p>
            When you check a case as learned,
            your progress automatically saves even after refreshing or reopening the website.
        </p>

    </div>

